title: Desk Clamp for Articulating Desk Lamps (V2!)

description.text:
I bought a brand-new articulating desk lamp at a garage sale for $2, minus a base, and needed a way to fasten it to my desk so that I could use it.   
This clamp will work with lamps with a base-shaft size of ~12-13mm, and with desks less than 4-5cm thickness, depending on the fastening method. It was designed with a nut trap for a 1/4"-20 nut, and for a 1/4"-20 bolt or threaded rod. I used a cap-head bolt and a 1/4"-20 knob I had laying around, but a knob for this could be printed quite easily.  
EDIT: Updated files to V2. V2 includes a base that interlocks with the body of the clamp, and was designed for increased stability. V2 also includes knobs and pads (placed at the end of the bolt so that it won't bite into the bottom of the desk) for 1/4"-20 hex and cap-head bolts (a bolt between 1.5" and 2" is recommended).  
EDIT: I printed V2 and uploaded photos. I works! The newly added interlocking base and screw pad eliminated all of the wobble not attributable to the lamp itself, and the pieces fit together well with very minimal trimming. Enjoy!

Plenty sturdy when printed at 20% (honeycomb) infill, but print at higher density if you plan on hitting it with a hammer (?).   
The nut traps are tight fitting, so you might need to heat them a bit with a lighter to press the nuts into place.

A pair of laser cut hooks for holding the xmas stockings on the fireplace mantle without the need of a strong counter weight.  This version is made for a mantle/ledge that's 1.5in thick.  You'll need to measure your ledge and adjust this measurement to match.  If it's not at least fairly snug, it won't hold reliably. 
This is also designed with quarter inch wood in mind for the notches where the pieces slot together.  If you're using a different thickness wood, you'll need to adjust this as well.  I won't recommend anything thinner than 1/4in.  I considered trying 1/8th, but I'm convinced it wouldn't work well.  It just wouldn't be strong enough.

This is a fire hydrant birdhouse with 1-5/8" diameter entrance. I added several drain holes on the floor and added holes in center of the three nuts to act as ventilation. New update .stl and 3dsMax files and download from http://maxvantageasia.com/max3dPrints/carbonTubeCutter.html This is my new design for cutting carbon tube tool with a Dremel Multi395/3950. It designed to cut carbon tube from 10 to 40 OD and max 2 mm thickness , that is very useful for model maker. In order to complete this project, you need to have
  • M6 x 80 bolt x 1 , nut x 2 , washer x 2
  • M3 x 16 bolt x 6 , nut x 6 , washer x 12
  • 12 x 6 x 4 bearing x 8
  • 6 x 40 bearing shalf x 5
  • OD28.5 x 30 ( longest length you want to cut ) carbon tube
    • Also, of course you need a Dremel Multi395/3950 with a OD 60mm cutting disc. This time I prepared the metal parts for people who needs or if you don't want to print yourself, you can order to me via email : [email protected] . https://www.facebook.com/ricky.cheung.94043/videos/1030018230353842/ https://www.facebook.com/ricky.cheung.94043/videos/1033049330050732/ Additional dusts collector parts was added. I use a common vacuum cleaner with a hose diameter from 31 to 35. No more mess around when cutting. The main body did revised but if you don't want to print again, just use some tape cover the openings inside. Also, you need to cut a hole with 20 diameter on the 28mm tube and 120mm from end of the tube. In order to suck the dusts out. Above are the videos on Facebook I put, if you are interested, go there to have a look. DISCLAIMER Please be informed that the Carbon Fiber Dust is highly toxic to everyone. And breathing it without proper respiratory protection is at risk. Please take good care yourself when cutting the carbon tubes. Thank you for your download!

author: FatFarlake

description.text:
Through testing I've found that much of the jerk wobble in printing with higher accelerations comes from the acrylic y-carriage vibrating when the y axis movement changes directions.
I had an idea that because the bearings were places so far from the bed level screw holes it gave the carriage the ability to vibrate up and down.
I designed a new y-carriage where bearings were places as close to the bed level holes making it nearly impossible for the bed to vibrate up and down on sudden movement changes. Also made use of four bearings instead of three. This way all four corners of the bed is as stable as can be. Additionally the bed height is 8mm with the screw holes being very tight fit to M2 screws. With this addition the screws are very tightly fixed in the carriage.
NOTE: The RadialBearingHolder file is for creating your own bearings using 623ZZ radial bearings. I use this setup and it has worked wonders for my system in terms of printing fast, precise and with high acceleration.

title: aerostock compatible parts for Misumi rail

description.text:
Fully integrated carriages for Misumi SSEB13-420, use 8mm M3 bolts to attach.  
Magnet insets are built for the 1/2" ring magnets available from Magcraft.  
Simple shrouds can be used to aid in pouring the epoxy ball set with no mess in a single pass.  They're sized to seat a 1/2" ball.  
Arm spacing is exactly the same as Aerostock carriage.  The end effector is unchanged except for the hole size for the magnets.  
The effector for minamalist is sized up large enough to squeeze on a QUBD minimalist exturder and it's default mount plate with just a little cutting and drilling.  I only used it to test a litlte bit and it's not very clean.  Included just for completeness.

Insert the magnets with a little bit of superglue to hold them in place  
Paint acetone on the mating surfaces of the shroud and around the face of the magnet, place the shroud over the magnet with the thick part on the top side.  
Once dry a light smear of JBWeld epoxy to wet the entire surface of the ballseat is all you need.  Carefully drop a 1/2" ball bearing wrapped in plastic wrap into the seat and wait for the epoxy to cure.  
The balls will release fairly easily once the flash has been cut away and they're given a light twist with a pair of pliers.  I used another small stack of magnets to pull them straight out of the seat.

description.text:
Horn for the American Gramophone Co. Type Q Gramophone, a 100+ year old music player!  
When my beloved grandmother passed away, she left me a gramophone by the American Gramophone Co. Unfortunately, it was missing the horn. It's been re-created based on photographs from the web and modeled in Solidworks.

The STL is a surface that's offset from the outer diameter of the gramophone's sound outlet.   
The part is roughly 7in tall and 3.25in in diameter  
Set perimeter layers to 3, printing from the outside-in with 1.75mm PLA filament. Ultimately the wall thickness should be around 1.9mm.  
Position the part with the wide end facing down.

A printable turntable that uses marble instead of ball bearing, ball bearing are hard to come by instead of marble ball although they are not round like ball bearings.
This one intended for my friend's project for his turret driven by servo and to stabilize the toy gun during movement.
There are herringbone gears and servo mount as well, the servo mount will drive the turntable from the side and ratio are 1:1
You can mount the servo mount object to a servo or motor and have your turntable rotate the way you wanted by either remote driven or constant turn
It is also able to withstand  heavy object, probably 10-20kg, tried with a large roughly 1.5m x 1.5m whiteboard, and it spins verywell

Openscad file The openscad file are somewhat in a mess and I don't have the mood to fix and clean them. But it can be used just that you need to tinker with the code yourselves. You can customize the parameters and export the stl files to your liking Do be aware that the herringbone gear will make the rendering process much slower due to many polygons and unseen holes inside the gear itself due to original scripts included. The public domain gear must be included as well to generate the gear Object Files There are 3 object files; top, bottom and servo. you can use either side as the turntable e.g. top and top or bottom and bottom (theoretically, unless you disabled the herringbone gear on the openscad for top side) both of them has screw mounts only different placement, amount and area. For a servo or motor driven turntable you need to use all 3 of them each and you will have a motor driven turntable

UPDATE I have updated the model, making certain parts of the design thicker so that it is easier to print. You can find the new version under the downloads tab - it's called "sturdier visualizer". Objective: To picture the regions of the heart from which the bioelectrical signal (wave of depolarisation) is originating and use this to better interpret an ECG readout.
Audiences: Medical students, AP biology students, anyone who has recently had an ECG and is interested in learning where each of the signals is coming from
Preparation: A basic understanding of heart anatomy and the conducting system of the heart
Steps: Print and look.
Results: This is meant to be used a tool during an introduction to ECG interpretation. The next step (and potential assessment of what they learned) would be for the students to look at a real trace and determine the electrical axis. As a part of my training to become a medical doctor, I have been tasked with learning to read an Electrocardiogram (ECG). This is an essential part of every medical student's physiology exam and indeed, is one skill that you pretty much know that you will get to use once clinical training has begun. Therefore, it struck me as terribly strange and, quite frankly, irresponsible that it was taught so badly, as the ability to quickly diagnose and localise a heart attack or other pathological heart condition could mean the difference between life and death. All of the standard textbooks use the same empty phrases, the same 2D images showing the chest from the exact same frontal view. There are a plethora a Youtube videos but who has the time to search through them all to find one that will actually be useful (watching one on the topic takes roughly 15 minutes and what med student has that kind of time to spare?). An ECG is a non-invasive technique that provides graphical representation of the electrical activity of the heart.
The ECG is a 2D trace on a piece of paper. Okay. But, my professors kept repeating that we have to imagine the electrical activity moving in 3D in order to understand what the different traces are telling you. There are typically 12 (sometimes just 6, sometimes 15, there could just be one) different traces originating from 9 different electrodes and 3 leads (Electrode = a physical terminus placed on the patient (either + or -); Lead = an imaginary axis created between electrodes with both a positive and negative terminus). The way you read it is you compare the different heights and orientations of the PQRS waves and use that to decide the direction in which the wave of depolarisation is travelling. All the sources tell you where you should put the sticky pads of the electrodes on the body so that you can pick up the signal but it's more difficult to find and imagine where the signal is actually coming from. Now, this may have just been me, so please feel free to stop me at any point, shake you head at my stupidity and tell me that you can't believe I didn't get it from the diagrams but I felt that I needed to actually make a connection between the anatomy and what each of these stupid little lead abbreviations and numbers meant before I could even begin to look at a trace. I rejoiced when I found a little table on geekymedics.com that told me that, for example, V3 and V4 (the first two precordial leads) tell us about the electrical activity in the heart's anterior wall. Therefore, if I could combine what the faint ECG trace was telling me with some anatomical knowledge, perhaps I could figure out that the hypothetical patient's left anterior descending artery is the one with the obstruction. However, I still wanted to be able to imagine all of the leads and electrodes, all at once. So I designed this. Now, it must be noted that the beautiful heart at the centre of the design was originally created by Mvetto (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:426800) and this was then further modified by huntgatherer98 (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:693895) to make it more solid and ergo more easily printable. This technically makes this a remix of a remix, however while the heart in the centre it gorgeous and wonderfully accurate, its purpose in this design is to give the viewer an idea of where the ECG leads are picking up their electrical signals from. I haven’t printed it yet because I am on vacation away from my printer but I will be sure to do so when I get back in January. When I was a little blue at being unable to figure the damn thing out, I turned to 3D design and began by making a 360 degree quick little arrow dial based on that standard diagram that all the textbooks have. You can use it to figure out the mean electrical axis according to electrodes I, II, and III, and leads aVR, aVF and aVL. If the ECG trace for any of these has an inverted wave, that means that the signal is travelling in the opposite direction to it. If it is travelling perpendicular to it, it will show on the trace as a biphasic trace (the wave is small and resembles a sine wave more than a PQRS complex). I turned the design into a keychain in case any of you want it. That’s all for now. I’ll surely be updating the design as more modifications occur to me. I welcome any and all suggestions. I’m still learning myself so if I made any errors please let me know so that I may correct them.

title: Traxxas Spartan Driveline Alignment Fitting
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The purpose of this part is to permanently align the stuffing tube, transom, and strut of the Traxxas Spartan. It is designed to replace the rubber transom plug (#5725) with a solid fitting to engage the transom and stuffing tube. The fitting also engages the transom mounted strut (#5727, #5727R, or like) of the boat resulting in constant alignment. Through extensive testing we have found this to be the main issue with the design of the boat. The tube has excessive mobility in the transom and the strut has excessive mobility in it's mounting to the transom. The misalignment between these three parts leads to accelerated wear and reliability issues. The misalignment also contributes to the poor performance of the boat for example: torque roll, chine walking, and loss of speed.
We will be continuing development of this part as time allows to improve functionality including but not limited to: cooling pickups, ride pad/transom fixes, changes, & modifications. Version 0.6 Pre-Release pending further long term testing and modification. The entire concept was researched and developed in house and may be revised within the purpose outlined above.
Stay tuned for further changes Including a separate version for use with the larger diameter stuffing tube that has become a popular modification for the Spartan. Feel free to comment good or bad. Happy Printing :)
-S&G Design

The fitting is designed to engage the internal hull transom plastics, the outer hull shell may need reamed to provide proper fitment. O-Rings required for installation are:
1x- 5mm (ID) Section width of 2mm
2x- 7mm (ID) Section width of 1.5mm This was an early design made with the MakerWare slicer on default High settings with reduced print speeds.
We will update with RepG settings in the near future upon full v1 release.

As you may already know, I wanted a D20 that had "20" on each side. Shamelessly abusing my power as a blogger for MakerBot, I asked the citizens of Thingiverse to create one for me. ( http://www.makerbot.com/blog/2011/09/29/openscad-challenge-regular-icosahedron/ ) Polymaker was the first to post a solution and win the prize. ( http://www.makerbot.com/blog/2011/09/30/polymaker-dont-mess-with-him-that-dude-rolls-20s/ ) (Though, really prize might be overstating the value...) I tried printing several icosahedrons at different sizes and resolutions, but none of them seemed to come out very well. Most of the time the extruder would snag the die and pull it off the build platform. Finally I adjusted the design a little in OpenSCAD and printed the D20. Here's what I did:
  • I used OpenSCAD to scale the D20 down to about 30mm in diameter.
  • I added a thin, 1mm circular disc, 30mm in diameter, underneath the D20.
  • I positioned the die so that it was hovering 0.25mm above the surface of the disc.
  • I printed with support structures on. (But this may not have been necessary)
    • The big flat disc allowed the die to maintain contact with the build surface and it never came off. And, being placed 0.25mm above the disc allowed the die to pop right off very easily without any sanding or stray threads.

• Print!
  • Win like Charlie Sheen!
